<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Sherborne Transport Action Group (TIC 107)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#008080; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from Sherborne Transport Action Group (TIC 107)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Sherborne Transport Action Group (STAG) aims to improve transport provision for the people of Sherborne and the surrounding villages, particularly to help those </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">without access to a car and to encourage car owners to use other modes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">STAG welcomes all who have an interest in its objects.  Members may include representatives of town and parish councils, transport-related organisations, transport-providers and other</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> interested members of the community.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">This submission was agreed by STAG at its meeting on 19 September 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The great majority of enquiries into local transport have concentrated almost wholly on the context of cities and large towns.  We welcome the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">emphasis of the current enquiry .  We hope, however, that it will include not only areas which are truly isolated, but also the rural areas which cannot be regarded as isolated, but where the dispersal of population raises issues entirely different from th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ose of the large urban areas.  Sherborne</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> with a population of 10,000 and surrounding villages</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of a few hundred, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">come</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> firmly in this category.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How do Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities (i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ncluding rural and urban areas and island communities)?</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Local authorities should integrate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> local transport requirements </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> development plans (see Annex 1).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.2 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The most common approach </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to assessing current demand </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is to count passengers.  However, the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> key question is not how many people currently use buses, but how many others might be persuaded to use them and why they do not do so.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Surveys must be addressed to the whole population.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e.g. people with disabilities, older people, young people) taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The bread &amp; butter for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the smaller</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> operators lies in schools contracts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  But the extension of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">leaving age to 17 has generated an increased demand which is not being met adequately</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Outside the school service</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, daytime buses have become almost a social service for the elderly.  </span></li></ul><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.2 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, a healthy bus industry</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> cannot survive on special-interes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t groups alone.  It</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> must embrace</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a range of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> fare-paying passengers: either those with no cars, or those who might </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be persuaded that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a good bus service </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">more attractive than the hassle of finding parking space.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Those who travel to work are a key market; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">they need the early evening services to get home.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Too little attention is c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">urrently given to attracting the fare-paying</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> market.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">communities? How can these challenges be overcome?</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The main challenge is that the low</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> density of passengers does not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">support</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a commercially viable service.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  There is a conflict for bus operators betwee</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n a fast main road route and a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">uch slower one thro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ugh the villages.  We </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">need an efficient mechanism for getting village passengers to and from a stop on the main road</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, or to the railway station</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.2 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The situation is exacerbated by excessive regulation.  In particular, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the appl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cation of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">competition law appears to be predicated </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">wholly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">on an environment in which a viable competitive market may be expected</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Where that is not so,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the actual services to passengers (NOT </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cus</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">omer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, which is the transport authority</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) are impaired</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> by competitio</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n rules</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is of note that wealthy parts of the country </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> with others following suit) are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> permitted to operate an almost entirely managed system, with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the service entirely defined by the local transport authority and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">competition confined to who wil</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l actually supply</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the service</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Rural areas also need the flexibility to derive their own approach to competition.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Inadequate reimbursement for the concessionary fares scheme is another major challenge (see Annex 2).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do Community Tr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ansport services address the needs of passengers in isolated communities? How could Community Transport be improved?</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Community Transport services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">can be extremely valuable in filling gaps</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">but cannot meet the fundamentals of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a public </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">transport service</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hey </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">depend on either grant funding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cross-subsidy from commercial operations,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">volunteer operators</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">probably a combination of these</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> elements</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  So long as these remain available, a service </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> viable.  But it is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vulnerable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> model</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Community T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ransport can work well</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on a small and very local scale</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  But even the medium-size Community Interest Companies will not have the capacity to serve all isolated villages.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The weakness of these models is that they are based in the towns, and therefore incur dead mileage in serving outlying communities.  We need a much more flexible approach to regulation in order to e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ncourage people </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in those communities to offer the service.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The local </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">resident</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> who is prepared to offer a flexible service</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, to a nearby town or to a main bus route,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> should be able to do so with an absolute minimum of regulation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">no more than is esse</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ntial</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">safety of passengers and other road users.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> In a village where everyone knows the people involved, there is less need for protection against the rogue operator.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associated with funding transport services in is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">olated communities? How can these services be made more affordable?</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These services have been made </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">less</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> affordable, both for passengers and for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">subsidising transport authorities, by the combined effect of increased fuel costs, decreased support for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the con</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">essionary fares scheme, and reduction in the Bus Services Operators' Grant (BSOG).  It was a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">grave </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">misjudgement to impose</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> not one but two reductions in government funding at the same time as world market prices for fuel  were increasing rapidly.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.2 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Regulation and competition law are based on the context of large urban areas.  The situation is entirely different in rural or isolated communities.  For </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rural </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">bus companies, co-operation is more important than competition. eg operators with garages at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">opposite ends of a route might combine so that the first bus starts, and the last bus ends, at its own garage. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Annex 1</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Relation of Public Transport to Development Planning</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Provision of public</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> transport ought to be assessed in the overall context of planning.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  This is made more difficult by the fact that transport is a County re</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ponsibility, while planning lies with the Districts.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Active integration is needed.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The current criteria for the crea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tion of Local Plans call for assessment, in deciding how rural areas should develop, of the overall effect on the cost of services to a community. The absence of accessible public transport will increase those costs. It has the effect of excluding many of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the very elderly, who are present in increasing numbers, from any community or business centre which is less than a very few miles from their home (anecdotal evidence from the property market suggests 7 miles). This alienation, once it has occurred, is irr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eversible. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is a compelling case for providing housing in the villages for younger people so that schools and other facilities remain viable.  However, i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t would be perverse to decree an increase in the need for distributed social/affordable housing i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n isolated rural communities without costing in a long-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">term subsidy for transport. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hose with a real need may be expected to have a greater requirement for public transport to access not only retail but increasingly necessary social and health services. Wi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">thout a transport subsidy, the effect would otherwise be to create rural communities which are increasingly made up of the relatively wealthy middle aged, whose contribution to local costs is currently limited by the absurdly low top band of Council Tax. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The relative cost to local government of servicing those of the population who are in fact frail, immobile or poor would therefore be reduced by not encouraging these people to live in isolated communities.  But it must be questioned whether this would be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">socially acceptable.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Annex 2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impact of the over-60 Concessionary Fare Scheme</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There are very few people who fully understand the Concessionary Fare Scheme.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  We have encountered firm statements from local authority representatives which are i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">flat </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">contradiction with the actual situation.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  However, several factors stand out:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.  The scheme was introduc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ed on the basis that it would be fully funded by central government.  While one recognises the right of a government to vary the undertakings of its </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">predecessor, it is deeply regret</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">able that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">'</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">' (of whatever party)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> has reneged on this and thereby </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">destroyed the foundations of the scheme.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Given the constraints on local authority funding, the reduction in central provision means that the operators are squeezed.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The original maxim that operators should neither gain nor lose by the scheme is no longer being honoured.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.  The basis of calculating reimbursement is extremely coarse</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, with a single reimbursement rate whatever the length of journey.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Some authorities </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">work on an 'average fare' across all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of an operator's routes.  The reimbursement rate is thus </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">dominated by</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> short urban routes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(the large majority)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and is wholly inadequate for the long rural routes.  This results</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">perverse </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">transfer of funds from long r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ural routes to short urban routes, contrary to the economic stresses.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.  Since the reimbursement rate is based on the average of cash fares (often a tiny minority of passengers) there is an incentive to keep those cash fares high and to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">avoid offering an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> discounted fares such as off-peak </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r promotional periods. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> This militates against attracting new fare-paying passengers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4. There is widespread evidence that many passengers would be prepared to pay a modest fare rather than having entirely free travel,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> if this would secure the future of a route.  However, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">such flexibility is not permitted</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> under the rules of the national scheme.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>